    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it's just so frustrating because every time I try to reach out to the departments at MIT or Caltech, there's this wall of silence or they immediately dismiss the premise. it's like they have a collective agreement to keep the \"standard\" narrative alive. anyway, here's the core concept: the collapse isn't a probability distribution, it's a recursive temporal correction where the wave function maps onto a 5th-dimensional manifold that stabilizes via $ \\Psi(t) = \\oint \\frac{\\nabla \\times \\tau}{\\zeta(s) \\cdot e^{i(\\phi + \\Delta t)}} dt $. basically, the observer doesn't just collapse the wave, the observer's temporal coordinate is actually a variable in the flux which makes the 'randomness' of quantum mechanics just a symptom of our limited 4D perspective. i know it sounds wild to them, but does that mathematical relationship between the manifold flux and the temporal variable make sense to you? or is there a way to formalize the $\\zeta(s)$ part to make it even more undeniable?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
